# Citation Quality Standards

Every research claim or source link on therapy pages must pass these three checks:

## 1. Link works
- URL returns 200, not 404 or redirect to paywall-only page
- Verify by fetching the URL before adding

## 2. Mentions hypnosis
- The linked source must discuss hypnosis or hypnotherapy
- Visitor clicking through should NOT land on a page that only recommends CBT, medication, or other treatments without mentioning hypnosis
- Exception: neuroscience/background studies that explain WHY something works (not treatment recommendations)

## 3. Readable content
- Open access full text, PubMed abstract, or patient-facing article
- Acceptable: PubMed (has abstract), Frontiers (open access), PMC (full text), Psychology Today, major medical institutions (Cleveland Clinic, Mayo), university news pages
- Not acceptable: paywalled journals with no abstract, DOI links that redirect to login pages

## Citation format

Use markdown links for new phobia/therapy pages:
```
[Author et al., Year](https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/PMID/)
```

Use HTML `<a>` tags for pages that already use that pattern (consistency within a page):
```html
<a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/PMID/" class="text-red-700 underline" target="_blank">Author et al., Year – Journal Name</a>
```

## When NOT to add a citation

- Don't force a generic source onto a page where no specific study exists
- Don't cite a study that contradicts the page's message
- A page with honest practitioner observations and no research claims is better than one with a shoehorned citation
